com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> &quot;If you like, I can take you to Thurgadin since I have to stop there before continuing towards Skyshrine. If you are going to wander in that region beware of the Ry`Gorr orcs and Kromrif giants. The orcs and giants have an alliance and are at war against the Coldain. The dwarves actually built their city in a mountainside and is hidden behind a waterfall to prevent invasion by the frost giants.&quot; The ranger reached for an unused piece of parchment and quill, and drew a rough map as she explained how to access the city.<br>
<br>
~~~<br>
<br>
The Dragon Portal of the Great Divide.<br>
<br>
A tear in the fabric of time and space opened up and allowed the Feir`Dal ranger, the Koada`Dal wizard, and half elven druid to appear within the obsidian ring. Millikin habitually turned and looked up at the statue of the dragon guardian. After an exchange of coin and word of thanks, the druid traced a rectangular pattern in midair and vanished in a swirl of mist. <br>
<br>
The biting chill wind was the first thing to grab Shiobahn's attention as she examined the landscape. For as far as the eye could see was snow, looming black cliffsides or mountain peaks. She pulled her cloak closer around her form and followed Millikin's direction in the south.<br>
<br>
&quot;The mad sorceror Velketor makes his lair in one of the caves that way. The Coldain say he sometimes kidnaps their people for experiments and even his own people, the Kromzek spurn him. I've explored the caves a bit. He has golem constructs and gargoyles guarding the entrances to his castle. Mostly I've encountered giant spiders or kobolds there though. There's also whispers of a dissident sect of Coldain making a hideout in the caves out here. I've not had the chance to confirm that as of yet though.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It sounds as if you've gotten involved in the politics of the Coldain, Cousin. Despite your experiences in Freeport.&quot; Shiobahn smiled to the ranger.<br>
<br>
Millikin shrugged slightly. &quot;They are at war with the those who encroach upon the Tunarean Court. 'The enemy of my enemy is my friend' I suppose you could say. And Thurgadin, our destination, is due north. Barring any accidents or delays, we should reach the city in an hour or so. It gets cold out here at night.&quot;<br>
<br>
As the two headed north, the ranger continued her discourse of the local inhabitants and creatures of the area and how to best combat or avoid them. Shardwurms roamed near the mountain peaks near their lairs within and seemed to blend into the background with their white scales. Until they unleashed their chilling breath weapon. The primitive yaklike humanoid tizmak made their home in a network of caves in the western mountain sides. Feral kodiaks wandered the eastern and southern mountain range. Finally Shiobahn saw the outline of a Coldain guard tower near a river and faintly heard the roar of a waterfall. Out of the corner of her eye, she saw a shadowy outline rushing towards them...  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(7/1/02 3:09:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> Trip to Third Gate (Another Interlude)<br>
<br>
  &quot;Milli, I kind of need your help with something.&quot;  The half elven rogue known to most as Corvariel Nytewisp ran his fingers through his hair and smiled his most charming smile to the Feir`Dal ranger who was perched on the roof of the Hidden Inn in East Commonlands.<br>
<br>
  &quot;With what?&quot;  Millikin called from her vantage point.  She noticed two orcs carrying a wooden crate from one of their encampments.  The sight had apparently become a commonplace occurrence lately from Clan Deathfist and she had decided to find out what was going on.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You remember that wonderful spear you gave me awhile back.  From Luclin?&quot;  <br>
<br>
  &quot;Mmm hmm.&quot;  Millikin replied, her attention had focused on the Freeport Militia guard that was patrolling nearby.  One of the orcs approached him.  Though too far away to hear, Millikin was perceptive enough to realize that a conversation of some sort was taking place.  Then suddenly the guard drew his sword and ran the orc through.  This was not totally unexpected but the fact that the guard had even entertained a parley with the Deathfist was what piqued the ranger's curiosity.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Well, I lost it.&quot;  Corvariel paused for dramatic effect before continuing.  &quot;Somewhere in Neriak.&quot;  He leaned against the wall and waited.  Millikin froze at the last statement then jumped from the roof in front of Corvariel.<br>
<br>
  &quot;What in the Nine Hells were you doing in Neriak.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Truth be told he was attempting to pilfer from one of the guildmasters, but he wasn't about to tell Millikin that.  He knew she took a dim view of stealing as a rule.  He smiled once again.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I was uhm -- sightseeing.  Yes.  I'd never been to Neriak before and thought since I was passing by I may as well go ahead and check it out.  Anyway, I was minding my own business but apparently a few of the dark elves didn't much care for my dropping in unannounced.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Uh huh.&quot;  Millikin looked straight at him.  If that wasn't the wateriest lie she'd ever heard in her life, it certainly ranked up in the top five.  Nonetheless Corvariel smiled again at her as if to say 'That's my story and I'm sticking with it.'<br>
<br>
  &quot;Where about did you lose it?&quot;  Millikin sighed, foreseeing a trip to Neriak in her immediate future.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I believe the sign said Third Gate.&quot;  Corvariel stated innocently.  Millikin stared at him.  While she was not familiar with the city firsthand, it was a well known fact that the Third Gate was the heart of Neriak where the rich and powerful lived.  And that included their clergy and practitioners of the dark arts.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Just sightseeing, huh?&quot;  A touch of sarcasm laced Millikin's remark.  &quot;So tell me, did this tour entail visiting the palace of their queen?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Oh nothing so grandiose.  Just their training hall for rogues.  Of course I couldn't pass by and not look in.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Of course not.&quot;  Millikin remarked caustically as the two headed towards the tunnel that led to Nektulos Forest.<br>
<br>
~~~~~<br>
<br>
Making it past the city gate sentries was not overly difficult for either the ranger or rogue but moving silently and unnoticed through an entire city without the use of magic was more difficult.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You could probably use your invisibility spell here -- &quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Camouflage.&quot;  Millikin interrupted.  &quot;Spellcasters use invisibility.  Rangers and druids use camouflage.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Yeah, whatever.&quot;  Corvariel dismissed the remark.  &quot;As I was saying, it may not be a good idea to cast spells deeper in the city.  They have a lot of spellcasters that might pick up on it.  I just need you to get rid of anyone that might see us.  Maybe toss their bodies in the water or whatever.&quot;<br>
<br>
Corvariel moved towards the stone bridge that sloped down and led into a checkpoint tower.  Millikin grabbed him by the shoulder and pulled him back to whisper (somewhat loudly) in his ear.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;You know, it is activities of that sort which invite retaliation.  While you may not care overmuch, I'd prefer that Kelethin and Felwithe not turn into a site for assassination games.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;If they see you they'll kill you.&quot;  Corvariel added.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Then I'll deal with them then.  But this is their home and we're asking for trouble by coming here.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Yaa, fine then.  When you get past the checkpoint go right and make a sharp turn left.  Before you get to the fountain, turn right and head down that passage and stop at the pool.  I'll meet you there.  Don't go much further as there's a guardhouse nearby and the city commons area has a series of portcullis gates to deter intruders and invaders.  The guards control the opening and shutting of those gates.&quot;<br>
<br>
Millikin nodded at the directions and sprinted down the slope and past the check point.  The guards standing at either side either took no notice of her or saw the eldritch lightning coursing through the sword blades in either hand and instantly decided that they would not interfere unless a general alarm was sounded.  Millikin paused at the water fountain just before she could resume in the direction Corvariel had outlined previously, a single guard had come around the corner from one of the shops further down the path.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You there.  Stop!&quot;  <br>
<br>
Millikin paid no heed to the demand to halt and continued along the twisted passageways until she stood at a ledge that overlooked a pool of water.  As she walked down the incline towards the tunnel mouth on the opposite side of the pool, Corvariel waved from the tunnel and began talking quietly.<br>
<br>
  &quot;The guardhouse is up ahead.  There's two you'll see at the far end and two offices at the other end of the main portcullis gate.  One or two guards are in either tower.  But there's two towers across from then that you can't see because they'll be behind us as we approach.  There's usually a guard or two inside those as well.  Once you're past the main portcullis and in the courtyard there are smaller once to either the left or right.  We want to head left this time.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Ten guards?&quot;  Millikin inquired.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Uh ... eleven actually.&quot;  I forgot.  There is one who wanders.  He patrols the outskirts of the commons areas and he'll come up close to here then turn back and continue his circuit.  They raise and lower the portcullis for him.  He's the captain of the watchguard or whatever.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Are you sure you know what you're talking about?  Capt. N`Farre is the captain of the guard and he was outside at the gate earlier.&quot;  Millikin looked at Corvariel and her eyes narrowed slightly.<br>
<br>
  &quot;The guard's nobody with any kind of rank really.  He's just in charge over here.  See, here he comes now.&quot;  Millikin heard the clinking of chains and looked up as Corvariel pointed as a dark elf guard in red trimmed silver armor headed their way.  The visor of his helm was pulled down as he strode purposely towards them.  Elf and half-elf alike stepped back into the shadows of the tunnel and suddenly the Teir`Dal did a sharp about-face and marched in the other direction.<br>
<br>
  &quot;We need to move now while the portcullis is up.&quot;  Corvariel suddenly took off running before Millikin could say another word.  Millikin quickened her pace when suddenly the guard they had seen earlier turned around suddenly.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Intruder!&quot;  In a blur of motion the dark elf drew his sword and sliced an overhead arc for Millikin's head.  A guard looked out from the tower and moved towards her.  The ranger brought her left sword, Earthcaller, up to block the swing and twisted her wrist as if to hilt punch the guard with Swiftwind, and the last moment, she snapped the edge of her blade towards his neck and pulled back, slashing his neck.  The Teir`Dal body's stiffened and his sword clattered to the ground as he fell.<br>
<br>
One of the guards called out as two of them advanced on the ranger.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You're that filthy Tunarean ranger&quot;  The guard who had spoken smashed his shield towards her face and caused her to stagger back a step while the other moved to try and flank her.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I'm not filthy.&quot;  The guard suddenly slumped over as one of Corvariel's throwing knives found itself imbedded between his ribs.  He was standing on the other side of the portcullis.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Stop playing around, Milli.&quot;  She didn't notice the two corpses slumped against the wall.  One had his throat slit and the other had a sliver of metal shoved right under his fifth rib<br>
<br>
  &quot;Close the gates!&quot;  One of the guards had the presence of mind to call out and the rattling of chains was heard.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Much as I'd love to stay for a dance or two...&quot; Millikin ducked a swing aimed for her head by her flanking guard and spun sideways to avoid a sword thrust aimed for her heart by a guard who had arrived at the alarm call.  &quot;I must be off.  Another night perhaps.&quot;  The ranger ran towards the lowering gates and dove for the ground, sliding just beyond the portcullis as it slammed into place.  She quickly stood up and dusted herself off, spitting dirt out of her mouth in the process.<br>
  <br>
  &quot;I wonder if this is what they mean by the saying everyone eats a pinch of dirt sometime in their life.&quot;  Corvariel smirked at her.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You may find yourself under six feet of dirt sooner than later.  Particularly once they get that portcullis back up.&quot;  Both heard the tell-tale creaking of chains to indicate it was being raised.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Right.  Lets go.&quot;<br>
<br>
The two ran down streets and alleyways of the commons section of Neriak and into the section called Third Gate.  A general alarm had been sounded and Neriak's guards were marching through the streets searching for them.  The two ducked into an abandoned building for a few hours until the ruckus about their presence died down.  Sitting down crosslegged behind some crates Millikin closed her eyes, while Corvariel paced near a window, peeking out occasionally.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You just had to be seen didn't you.&quot;  Corvariel whispered.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Not intentionally.  Besides, it was your idea to rush the gate, not mine.  And you're the reason I'm here in the first place.&quot;  Millikin responded complacently.  As had become habit, she reached up to make sure her medicine pouch was still around her neck, then stood up.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Yeah yeah.&quot;  Corvariel grumbled.  &quot;Anyhow, when we get to the training hall.  Just invis us and...<br>
<br>
  &quot;Camouflage.&quot;  Millikin corrected.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Whatever ... and I'll poke around until I find my spear.  You wait outside the hall.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;If you get caught stealing or something I am NOT going to help you.&quot;  Millikin looked at him dubiously.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;Me?  Steal?  I'm hurt you'd make such an accusation of me.  I just want to get my spear back.&quot;<br>
<br>
The two made their way towards the thieves guild.  And once the cantra was recited to render them invisible, Corvariel skipped up the steps unseen.  For her part, Millikin paced back and forth outside, stopping only once to inspect the statues in the front of the guildhall, with mild distaste.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Run!&quot;  Suddenly Millikin caught sight of Corvariel tearing out of the hall, his spear gripped in his hand.  Two dark elves were not far behind, weapons drawn.  She whispered another druidic cantra and one of the dark elves slowed his step.  He turned towards her cursing but she quickly ran after Corvariel.  She readied her bow and nocked an arrow, taking careless aim at his other pursuer.  The first shot missed but the second arrow hit him in the leg.  She lost sight of the rogue after the second shot and ducked down another alleyway.  Millikin was not surprised to see him near the city entrance gates on her way out.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I got what I came for.&quot;  He grinned at her, spear in hand.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I bet you did.&quot;  She looked at him suspiciously.<br>
<br>
  &quot;What?&quot;  Corvariel took a tone of feigned slight.  &quot;Here I was going to thank you and all and you accuse me of having an ulterior motive.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;I haven't accused you of anything yet.&quot;  Millikin looked at him.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Well, nonetheless, thank you anyway.  It means a lot to me.&quot;  Corvariel added deciding it best not press the issue to raise the ranger's suspicions right away.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You're welcome.  I think.  Until, later, Corv.&quot;  That said, the ranger transformed into a dark furred wolf and ran into the Nektulos Forest.<br>
<br>
~~~~~<br>
