<br>
&quot;When I came to this place of smooth evil, I understood the powers of the mind better than most men.  Black skies and white water ran across the beast's back. I could use its hidden abilities to touch others, read minds, and change the way they twisted.&quot;  -- Vlanic Kroskos<br>
<br>
<br>
  &quot;Faer mri' kul.&quot;  Raven Yadan swept into her study and raised a single hand in completion of a spell.  A silvery mist outlined the doors and windows of the room, preventing them from being casually opened by anyone, save the spellcaster.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;Good bye, Raven.&quot;  The enchanter discarded the trappings she wore to detail her disguise as her facial features became more angular and her ear tips more pointed.  Her skin darkened as the enchanter reverted to her natural form.  She set the spectacles on the table before her and sat down in an elaborately carved chair.  If the enchanter was inclined to gloat over her accomplishments, (Which is not to say she doesn't.) she would have reflected over how swiftly she learned of this journal's existence and how she legitimately obtained it.  <br>
<br>
The one eyed old human with two raven pets struck her as somewhat senile at first when she overheard him discussing an enchanter's journal one evening with another companion.  Nonetheless she listened, both in amusement and in the hopes that perhaps he may know something else of value.  Then he mentioned that the book was all but forgotten in the library of a sage in Felwithe who died recently.  The man had a half-brained scheme to steal the book but wasn't sure he could pull it off.  An idea quickly took shape in the enchanter's mind and she parted company.  It did not take her long to verify that the claims of a sage's death were indeed true.  The enchanter quickly created a persona and chose the name in homage of the two preternaturally intelligent birds and mockery of their owner.  She concocted a story about the journal belonging to a deceased relative who knew the sage when he was younger.  The sage's family was content to let her take the journal, thinking it little more than the personal diary of a human spellcaster.<br>
<br>
As it was though, the enchanter gave no further thought to the old man or his birds, only to what content of a forgotten book in Felwithe's archives could possibly be of interest to him.  She opened the journal and began to read...<br>
<br>
Hours later, she closed the book.  The implications in the journal were unexpected to be sure and if they proved to be true, the power she stood to gain would be remarkable.  Some of the spell research was incomplete or experiments were flawed but the former would be corrected with some modifications to the latter.  The only thing the enchanter needed was a suitable test subject.  Someone who's existence was inconsequential to her long term plans and meaningless to the people she currently threw in her lot with as she did not want to risk alienating them for the time being.  She opened the journal again to reread the requirements of the spell, already someone in mind, she began mentally formulating her experiment procedure. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uautumncrescendo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Autumn Crescendo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Auty the Primadonna</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(7/14/02 3:16:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> Great Divide - <br>
<br>
  Despite the enchantment of a magical skin Shiobahn was slapped to the side by a large paw that nearly encompassed half of her torso.  The second slap hit her and again though unscathed by her shielding it did not stop her from getting a bit dazed.  It would break through in a few more hits, but what was it.  Pulling herself up from the deep snow that bogged the pass, her eyes lifted to face her assailant, and she was face to face with the Kodiak.  Its eyes gleamed with raw fury, and its claws were in full extension from its paws, and again it tried mauling and maiming in large swinging strokes, a third and fourth glancing off her shield.  <br>
<br>
  Millikin was swift on the scene; she knew this type of combat was not one her cousin would last in.  Shiobahn was uttering the words to shackle the beast while dodging blows, and just as the spell took off Millikin was in control.  Energy crackled from the duel blades she wielded and she went into a fast and furious combat, the beast scarcely landing a solid hit on the nimble elf.  Shiobahn regained her composure as swiftly as she could, reaching her arms out as she called upon the power of the elements and invoked them into a fiery rain pelting down upon the Kodiak in waves.  Before she could even utter another spell though the beast was run through and crumpled to the ground.<br>
<br>
  Millikin gave a quick assessment of her cousin, assuring that there was nothing more than minor damage to be had.  Her eyes scanned down either side of the pass before falling more particularly on the snow.  Her tracking skills were keen and she wanted to make certain that their attacker had been alone.  Satisfied he was simply a wanderer she glanced back at her cousin.  <br>
<br>
"Perhaps you will want to use a shield of invisibility until we are safely at the city lines."<br>
<br>
Shiobahn nodded in agreement, glanced around a moment with some trepidation, then withdrew her spell book flipping with haste to the area she had her invisibility spell marked.  It took but a second to refresh the incantation to her mind before she felt certain enough to cast it.  Her fingers traced a series of runes in the air and in a moment she was cloaked in the stealth of invisibility.  <br>
<br>
"I am ready."  Shiobahn murmured to her cousin.<br>
<br>
"This way then."  Millikin gave a small tilt of her head to indicate direction before again into the snow.<br>
<br>
  Shiobahn marveled at how many people she saw in a mimicked fashion, skirting in the shadows of invisibility with her.  She touched the slim bone hoop earring Quasqueton had brought her as a gift from his travels, the enchantment allowing her the sight to spot those hiding in the folds of invisibility.  It was good to know she was not so alone as she lurked in the cold wastes.  The frozen stream caught her attention ahead.  The water was crisp and an icy blue, and the sounds of the waterfall that kept it moving came into hearing distance.  Curving around the river they ended up at the base of the falls and Millikin turned to regard her cousin.<br>
<br>
"Follow me around back, we will go behind the falls."  She called out over the heavy rush of water.<br>
<br>
"Behind?  This is what you spoke of when you mentioned their protection from the Giants, yes?"<br>
<br>
  Millikin nodded then slipped behind the falls, and passing by the guards that held the outposts at the front of the city.  Shiobahn scampered behind the waterfall as well and blinked coming into site of the Dwarves.  She was raised not so far from the city of Kaladim, and these Dwarves looked nothing like the ones of her homelands.  Their skin was so pale it was near transparent coming from years of never seeing the sun.  Their features were harsher, and more chiseled, almost a reflection of the world that surrounded them.  It was after a series of gates that the two parted ways.  A brief discussion on where the basic essentials could be found took place.<br>
<br>
"Be safe cousin, and good luck finding Quas…"  Shiobahn gave the ranger a quick embrace.<br>
<br>
"Thank you."  Millikin murmured, taken aback by the affection of her cousin.  "I should not have too much trouble finding him, he leaves a trail of disaster in his wake."<br>
<br>
"I know, isn't it fantastic?"  Shiobahn beamed.<br>
<br>
"I will never understand wizards…"  Millikin muttered as she walked off in search of a few fletching supplies for the road.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(7/17/02 1:10:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> Millikin exited Thurgadin, Shiobahn's letter was safely stowed in her backpack.  By nightfall she had reached the Eastern Wastes and the temperature was dropping rapidly.  Millikin looked at the rapidly darkening sky, a storm was approaching.  She smiled grimly to herself as she made her way to a Coldain shelter she knew was nearby.  An explosion and flash of orange light caught her attention.  The aroma of burning flesh and charred fur assailed her sense of smell and made her eyes water.<br>
<br>
The ranger quickly headed in that direction.  On occasion she saw the corpses of tundra kodiaks, dire wolves, orc scouts, even a snow griffin.  She sighed inwardly as she knelt down and inspected the snow for tracks.  None were visible, which means the perpetrator was most likely a spellcaster.  Why didn't people make use of the remains?  Corpses tended to attract scavengers.  Soon the snow was falling faster and the wind grew louder so that she almost didn't hear the approaching Kromrif.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Die Outlander!&quot;  The sight of forged velium flashed before her and ripped through the chain mesh tunic she wore, spilling blood on the white snow in front of her.  The ranger fell backwards and immediately rolled sideways to avoid the follow-up strike.  In moments she was on her feet, weapons drawn, a healing cantra passed her lips and the wounds immediately began to close.  Millikin circled behind the Kromrif as he turned with a slashing arc towards her.  In a blur of motion, she ran between his legs and slashed at the back of his knees.  The giant howled in fury and lashed out with his fist to connect with a solid crunch to her back as she ran in front of him.  The ranger stumbled a few paces and spun around in time to block his weapon thrust and counterblow to his elbow with Swiftwind.  The giant was wielding a dagger, but the blade was long enough to be considered a short sword by the elf's estimation.  The Kromrif scout swung his foot sideways to sweep the elf to the ground and was mildly surprised to see she only staggered slightly.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;By Rallos, you are more resilient than I expected, Outlander.  Mayhap there is a place for you alive as a servant.&quot;  The giant bantered as he saw the outline of the ranger backing away, he could hear her breath was ragged and grinned thinking this encounter would be over all too soon.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I've no intention of finding out.&quot;  Swords still in hand, the elven ranger traced a sigil in midair.  Magical energy coalesced briefly then flickered out.  Somehow she had miscast the spell.  &quot;Valdayana's thrice damned curse.&quot;  She sighed again.  Swiftly wiping her blades and sheathing them, Millikin turned and ran relying on the darkness from the approaching storm for cover.  The giant quickly followed, though his vision was not as good as the elf's.  The protective enchantment the ranger had enabling her to regenerate from injuries at an accelerated rate without calling upon a healing cantra would fade soon.  She quickly pulled herself up into the branches of a tree and readied her bow.  Soon she saw the Kromrif's outline and took aim.  The arrow tore through the giant's chest and he staggered.  He reached for the piece of wood and ripped it out, cursing.  The arrowhead was barbed.  Another arrow found itself imbedded in his shoulder and a third grazed his temple.  Hastily the giant turned and ran.  Millikin watched his departure as she dropped down from the tree more intent on finding cover from the approaching storm than giving chase.  She smelled smoke from a nearby campfire, and unless she was hopelessly lost she was fairly sure that Garadain Glacierbane's encampment wasn't too far away.  She headed in that direction.<br>
<br>
