<br>
<br>
&quot;No exorciser harm thee!  Nor no witchcraft charm thee!  Ghost unlaid forbear thee!  Nothing ill come near thee!&quot;  <br>
-- William Shakespeare<br>
<br>
<br>
Valdayana D`Varr struck a match and touched the flame to the first candle.  A black hole opened up from the ceiling and eldritch electricity crackled.  She did not look the least bit surprised to see Millikin fall through.<br>
<br>
  &quot;For once your timing is impeccable, Ranger.&quot;  She continued lighting the candles, watching as the ranger reoriented herself.  Millikin straightened as she looked around.  Eclectic did not begin to describe the laboratory. (Or was it a library?) The room was illuminated enough to permit reading but it was not bright.  One wall possessed several shelves of books from ceiling to floor.  Several paintings that adorned the walls were rather macabre.  One was a graphic depiction of a historical battle, another showing victims of a blazing inferno.  Still another painting portrayed zombies engaging in a murderous rampage through a city that bore a striking resemblance to Freeport.  The ranger shuddered and took note of a few other details;  a table holding jars, vials, and various glass containers, several scaly and furry victims of taxonomy were inside display cases or stands in different corners of the room alongside statuettes of various compositions ranging from clay to diamond.  Located across from the wall of bookshelves was a desk with papers and books stacked on it.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Careful what you touch, Ranger.  Some things here are worth more to me than your life.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;I'll keep that in mind.&quot;  Millikin remarked.  &quot;I'd have never thought Quasqueton could miscast that badly.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;He didn't exactly.  I had to cast a spell that would bring you here the next time you attempted to use magic to travel.&quot;  Valdayana replied as she walked over to a rather grotesque bookstand that resembled a clawed hand tearing forth from the ground.  She opened the book and turned through a few pages.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Where is here?  And what is that ... animal called?&quot;  Millikin's attention had turned to the stuffed brown rabbit with a small rack of antlers affixed to its head.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;You are in my home.  And that is called a jackalope.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;I've never heard of such a creature.&quot;  Millikin studied it for several moments.  &quot;It's not a real animal.&quot;  The ranger announced after a minute.<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot;  Valdayana shook her head.  &quot;It is something I created several years ago to catch the attention of the overly curious who are somewhat lacking in intellect.  Once again, it worked.&quot;<br>
<br>
Millikin glared daggers at the enchanter, who smiled slyly and added.  &quot;Though you are the first to realize it is fake.  Perhaps I should name it after you.  How does Milky strike you?&quot;  Finding the page she was searching for, she traced her forefinger along the page's script as she read.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;It does not strike me at all.&quot;  The ranger replied in a flat tone.  &quot;I know misery loves company but why else have you abducted me and brought me to your dismal abode?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Abducted?  That is a rather severe word.  Consider it a nontraditional invitation.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Abduction is an apt term.  You brought me here without my consent.  You do realize that abduction is a crime in any culture?&quot;  The statement was half-inquiry, half threat.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Not if there are no witnesses to the event or anyone alive to claim it happened.&quot;  Valdayana looked poignantly at Millikin to curtail the notion that her idea of a threat would intimidate her.  &quot;Bring me the silver jar on the table behind you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Millikin picked up the jar then paused as she contemplated telling her to get it herself before deciding that humoring the enchanter would be the fastest way to finding out what was up.  The medicine pouch she wore around her neck and intended to give the enchanter had been completely forgotten.  Valdayana took the jar and opened it, she recited a few phrases in an arcane language and passed the contents under Millikin's nose.  Millikin jumped backwards, startled both by the uncharacteristic act from the enchanter as well as the citrus aroma.<br>
<br>
  &quot;It's yuzu.  Used in some purification rituals and helps develop concentration and focus.  It should counteract the effects of your curse.&quot;  Valdayana explained, placing the jar back on the table.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You removed your curse?&quot;  Millikin eyed the enchanter warily.  Valdayana nodded and looked back into her book.  &quot;Why?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;I am researching a spell and you are going to help me with it.&quot;  She replied.<br>
<br>
  &quot;What spell?&quot;  <br>
<br>
  &quot;It's one I found in a journal during my studies.&quot;  <br>
<br>
  &quot;And this journal belongs to a friend of yours?&quot;  Millikin asked.  &quot;And I use the term friend loosely.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;It's not as if you know who Kintaz is, much less Alcina.&quot;  Valdayana answered loftily.  In truth, she wasn't exactly sure who Alcina was either.  The results of her research into the caster's identity was vague.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I know he's an enchanter and he developed the process used by the acolytes in the Temple of Solusek Ro to allow spellcasters to unlearn certain abilities.&quot;  Millikin retorted.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;Alcina is also an enchanter.  She developed her own series of spells that I found.  And if you quit interrupting me with your snide comments instead of relevant questions, I'll explain.&quot;  Valdayana was mildly impressed that a backwater ranger knew more about an enchanter than several fellow practitioners of the same form of magic could claim, though she wasn't about to say that.<br>
<br>
  &quot;What do you need me for?&quot;  Millikin asked after listening to Valdayana's prelect on the different effects of the spells she had uncovered.  Going on the presumption that Valdayana was telling her everything, (And Millikin doubted that was the case.) they all sounded like variants of several spells she'd already seen the enchanter employ so the significance of their discovery was lost on the ranger.  Besides, Valdayana did take advantage of the fact that she could cast a variety of spells (with annoying side effects) on the ranger without her consent, provided they were mostly non-harmful.  The ranger's curiosity at the discovery ended with Valdayana's explanation of their effects but suspicion of some other motive at work took form.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I wish to see if one of them can be used to induce a change in outlook and overall behavior.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;No.&quot;  The ranger stated emphatically, that sounded far too much like a charm spell for her tastes.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You have no choice.&quot;  Valdayana crossed her arms and smiled grimly at Millikin.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I'm not going to waste my breath arguing with you.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;You're being reasonable for once.  I anticipated that you'd be quite recalcitrant.  This will take less time than I expected.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;I'll show myself out.&quot;  Millikin turned and headed for the door.  Valdayana held up a hand and began another spell.  Millikin whirled around at the first syllables of the spell.  Time and again she heard that particular incantation, so she instantly recognized what the enchanter was now casting and knew what the effect would be, but inexperience in defending against the subtleties of enchantment led the ranger to react instinctively instead of rationally.  She drew her swords and charged towards the dark elf.<br>
<br>
Valdayana D`Varr held her ground, focused only on completion of her spell.  All she saw was the gathering of magical energy, the only sound she heard was her own sonorous chanting of arcane words to direct that energy.  It was a calculated risk because it was not impossible that the ranger could be within striking distance to disrupt her casting before she finished and she knew her protective magic would not last very long against a direct assault.  As the enchanter's attention returned to the physical world, she was greeted with the sound of steel clattering on stone.  Millikin stood unmoving.  Gone, however, was the ranger's taut stance, ever anticipatory of the necessity for a reaction.  The expression on her face was blank.  Valdayana knew the ranger's mind was in a haze and that she would not recall anything that happened while the spell was in effect. <br>
<br>
  &quot;I will make this as quick and painless as possible.&quot;  Valdayana slid the enchanted blades under the table with her foot as she took a vial from her pocket and dabbed her finger into the contents and traced a rune on Millikin's forehead, leaving behind a dark red smudge then recited a few arcane phrases.  There was a brief flicker of light as the rune she had traced vanished from natural sight.<br>
<br>
_____<br>
<br>
The spirit wolf paced back and forth.  The mental essence that separated wolf from elf been abruptly torn by a long forgotten magic ritual and it found it could not return to her.  The spirit wolf had watched their exchange and the dark elf's craven assault, powerless to intervene.  The enchanter had warded her from any sort of contact from supernatural creatures.  As the magic that had once called it to the ranger began to ebb, it realized that it had not been expunged entirely.  <br>
<br>
&quot;This act may come back to haunt you, Enchanter D`Varr.&quot;  The dark elf heard whispered as the wolf took corporeal form beside her.  Valdayana paused as she picked up another jar.  She did not hold any semblance of remorse for her actions but she was curious as to what creature Millikin had attracted as a protector.  The wolf was translucent and thin framed.  She knew its connection to the mortal plane was tenuous at best so the enchanter paid it little heed as she continued with her spellcasting ritual.<br>
<br>
  &quot;If you've any true regard for her welfare then you should know it is dangerous for her if you threaten me.&quot;  She held the jar over a candle flame, the contents ignited in a pale yellow flash and burned to make a bittersweet aroma.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Your exorcism was far from thorough.&quot;  The wolf growled softly.<br>
<br>
  &quot;It was sufficient to expel a mere totem spirit.&quot;  Valdayana traced a warding sigil in the direction of the wolf and with a single word banished him from the physical plane.<br>
<br>
_____<br>
<br>
  &quot;Coactu nutus...  Subsisto...&quot;  <br>
<br>
As the incantation came to a close, the ranger saw and felt a grey fog surround her.  Sight and sound blurred as a chill coursed through her body.  The ranger slouched forward as tension in her body departed, her grip on her swords loosened and they dropped unceremoniously to the ground.  The ranger could see, hear, and feel her surroundings but understanding had fled, higher consciousness had faded to meet the looming threat that faced her, the possible cessation of life as functions like metabolism, breathing, and blood circulation slowed to infinitesimal pace. <br>
<br>
  &quot;Exaudio.&quot;<br>
<br>
The enchanter's touch sent a surge of warmth through the catatonic ranger.  The magic's purpose was to insinuate itself into the wood elf's mental defenses, but the ranger's mind refused to acknowledge the strange force and continued its fugue cycle to ensure Millikin's basic life functions did not stop.  The spell's energy reverberated back to the enchanter.  <br>
<br>
Valdayana blinked, she was surprised to find any resistance considering the ranger foolishly fell to the initial and most obvious.  The dark elf closed her eyes in mental preparation for a contest of wills as she continued the spellcasting ritual, once more a current of eldritch force passed through the ranger, this time it merged with the ranger's mental processes, bolstering it as the magic trapping Millikin in a trance began to fade.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Nossas vontades transformam-se uma.&quot;<br>
<br>
The next thing Millikin recalled was the sickeningly sweet scent of crushed lavender and rose petals and seeing Valdayana with an opened vial in her hand, leaning wearily against a table.<br>
